nization-derived H2, strongly reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on native iron surfaces via a two-electron reduction. Fe0 serves as the strong reductant, donating electrons through surface oxidation (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+). The formate is activated by surface coordination and undergoes C-O bond cleavage with concomitant H-atom addition, yielding formaldehyde. Magnetite acts as co-catalyst for H2 activation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reduction of formate to formaldehyde is thermodynamically challenging but feasible with Fe0 as a strong reductant. Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated that native iron and iron-nickel alloys in hydrothermal systems can drive deep CO2 reduction. While direct formate-to-formaldehyde conversion is not as well-documented as CO2-to-formate, the strong reducing power of Fe0 in serpentinization environments (produced by olivine alteration) provides sufficient driving force. Herschy et al. (2014) also explored formaldehyde formation in alkaline vent simulations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to pyruvate on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"iron-rich hydrothermal conditions, multiple reduction steps on mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step CO2 reduction through surface-bound intermediates on magnetite: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate, proceeding through sequential C1 additions and reductive carboxylation on the mineral surface. The magnetite surface catalyzes both carbonylation and reductive steps, analogous to a proto-metabolic re", "