n_name\": \"histidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on greigite surface analogous to [Fe4S4] clusters. Hydride transfer from surface-bound H2 reduces CO2 to formate (HCOO-) via a two-electron reduction. The mineral acts as a structural and electronic analog to modern [Fe-S] cluster enzymes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is well-established as the first step in abiotic carbon fixation at alkaline hydrothermal vents. Demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020) and Roldan et al. (2015) who showed CO2 reduction on Fe3S4 surfaces under hydrothermal conditions, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway in biology (Sources 2546, 9371).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"black smoker or high-temperature hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction: CO2 + H2 \u2192 CO + H2O. Magnetite provides the catalytic surface for this reaction, which is thermodynamically favored at elevated temperatures. CO is a key C1 feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide minerals under hydrothermal conditions is well-documented. Magnetite (Fe3O4) catalyzes this reaction efficiently at 400-500K (Sources 19315, 2546). CO produced serves as feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of organic molecules.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in hydrothermal systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO + H2 \u2192 HCHO. Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite surfaces produces C1 oxygenates including formaldehyde as a primary product. CO dissociatively adsorbs on magnetite, and sequential hydrogenation yields formaldehyde before further reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on magnetite produces formaldehyde as one of the earliest C1 oxygenates (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Magnetite's catalytic function in FTT reactions was confirmed in carbonaceous chondrite studies (Source 19315). Formaldehyde is a critical prebiotic feedstock molecule (Sources 2655, 6942).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of glycolaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions producing C2 oxygenates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2CO + 2H2 \u2192 HOCH2CHO. C-C bond formation on the magnetite surface couples two C1 units, producing glycolaldehyde as the simplest sugar. This is a chain-growth step in the FTT mechanism.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on iron oxide surfaces produces C2 oxygenates including glycolaldehyde (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Glycolaldehyde has been detected as a product of FTT reactions and is a key prebiotic building block for sugars via the formose reaction (Sources 19315, 10209).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN synthesis from CO and NH3 on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-600K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"high-temperature vent environment, gas phase at mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO + NH3 \u2192 HCN + H2O. At high temperatures on pyrite surfaces, ammonia and carbon monoxide undergo dehydration condensation to form hydrogen cyanide. The iron-sulfur surface lowers the activation barrier for C-N bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN formation from CO and NH3 on mineral surfaces at high temperature is a well-established route. Pyrite catalyzes this reaction at black smoker temperatures (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997). HCN is a central prebiotic molecule serving as precursor to amino acids, nucleobases, and other biomolecules (Sources 9365, 21200, 9357).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 reduction on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, multi-step reduction CO2\u2192formate\u2192acetate\u2192pyruvate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate. Multi-step reduction on greigite/magnetite surfaces mimics the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway. Pyruvate is a central alpha-keto acid produced by carboxylation of the activated acetyl intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions by Cody et al. (2000) and more recently by Muchowska et al. (2017). This pathway parallels the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway in modern organisms. Pyruvate is a critical alpha-ketoacid hub in prebiotic metabolism (Sources 9332, 9400, 6987).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH3 from serpentinization, reducing hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate + NH3 \u2192 imine intermediate \u2192 reduction by H2/FeS \u2192 alanine. Reductive amination on mackinawite surfaces provides reducing equivalents for the imine-to-amine conversion. The mineral surface stabilizes the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids on FeS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been demonstrated by Huber & Wachtershauser (2006). This is a key step connecting prebiotic alpha-keto acid chemistry to amino acid biosynthesis (Sources 6987, 13450). Alanine serves as transamination donor for histidine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, Ca(OH)2 co-catalyst, mildly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2 HCHO \u2192 HOCH2CHO. Aldol condensation of two formaldehyde molecules catalyzed by borate and calcium hydroxide. Borate complexes stabilize glycolaldehyde against further polymerization. This is the initial step of the formose reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is well-established (Butlerow, 1861; Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate minerals stabilize sugars against degradation and channel the formose reaction toward biologically relevant products (Sources 10209, 9376). This provides a surface-environment route to the same C2 building block produced by hydrothermal FTT.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline evaporitic pool, borate stabilization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde + HCHO \u2192 glyceraldehyde via aldol condensation. The montmorillonite surface concentrates reactants and provides Lewis acid catalysis. Borate complexation stabilizes the glyceraldehyde product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation in the formose reaction produces C3 sugars from C2+C1 units. Montmorillonite catalyzes aldol reactions and stabilizes intermediates (Sources 9431, 15918). This step extends the sugar chain toward the C4 and C5 sugars needed for imidazole ring construction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay with borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, borate stabilization of sugar products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2 HOCH2CHO \u2192 erythrose (C4 sugar). Aldol condensation of two glycolaldehyde molecules forms erythrose. Montmorillonite surface catalysis and borate stabilization direct the reaction toward the C4 aldotetrose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to form C4 sugars is a well-established step in the formose reaction network. Borate minerals channel the formose reaction toward specific sugar products (Ricardo et al., 2004). Erythrose is a key precursor for C4+C1 Maillard-type imidazole formation (Sources 10209, 21200, 21196).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glyceraldehyde and glycolaldehyde to ribose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"borate complexation selectively stabilizes ribose over other C5 sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde (C3) + glycolaldehyde (C2) \u2192 ribose (C5) via aldol condensation. Borate complexes with the cis-diol motif in ribose, selectively stabilizing this pentose and preventing further degradation or polymerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ribose synthesis from C3+C2 sugars with borate stabilization is well-established (Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate minerals uniquely stabilize ribose among pentoses due to its cis-diol configuration. Ribose serves as a C5 building block for direct Maillard-type cyclization to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (Sources 10209).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), no ozone layer on early Earth\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HOCH2CHO + UV/TiO2 \u2192 OHCCHO + H2. TiO2 generates reactive oxygen species under UV irradiation that selectively oxidize the hydroxyl group of glycolaldehyde to an aldehyde, yielding glyoxal (1,2-dicarbonyl). The H2 or H2O byproduct removes reducing equivalents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO2-mediated UV photocatalysis is well-established in prebiotic chemistry for oxidative transformations. Glyoxal (the simplest 1,2-dicarbonyl) is a critical precursor for the Radziszewski imidazole synthesis. UV photocatalysis on TiO2 surfaces is prebiotically plausible given strong UV flux on the early Earth (Sources 9376, 9331).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Radziszewski imidazole synthesis from glyoxal, formaldehyde and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline conditions, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxal + HCHO + 2NH3 \u2192 imidazole + 3H2O. The Debus-Radziszewski synthesis: (1) 2NH3 attacks the two carbonyls of glyoxal forming a diamine intermediate; (2) formaldehyde provides the C-2 bridge carbon; (3) cyclization and aromatization via water loss yields imidazole. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and catalyzes the condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Radziszewski synthesis is a well-established, over 100-year-old reaction for imidazole formation from 1,2-dicarbonyls, aldehydes, and ammonia (Radziszewski, 1882; Debus, 1858). This reaction is considered prebiotically plausible given the availability of all three precursors. Montmorillonite catalysis enhances condensation reactions (Sources 9431, 15918). While unsubstituted imidazole is not on the direct path to histidine, it validates the Radziszewski mechanism used in the substituted variant (rxn_014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Maillard-type sugar-amine cyclization of erythrose with HCHO and ammonia to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation for aromatization step, wet-dry cycling, mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Erythrose (C4) + HCHO (C1) + 2NH3 \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (C5N2) + 4H2O + H2(oxidized by UV). Multi-step mechanism: (1) HCHO + NH3 \u2192 methanimine (H2C=NH); (2) Erythrose C-1 aldehyde + NH3 \u2192 imine at C-1; (3) Intramolecular Mannich-type reaction: methanimine attacks C-2 of the amino-sugar; (4) Second nitrogen cyclizes with C-1 carbon to close the 5-membered ring; (5) Sequential dehydrations and UV-driven oxidative aromatization yield the imidazole ring bearing the -CH2CHO side chain from the C-3,C-4 portion of erythrose. Two nitrogen atoms derive from two separate NH3 molecules. The C4+C1 carbon framework provides all 5 carbons. UV/TiO2 drives the aromatization (removal of H2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Maillard-type reactions between reducing sugars and amines are well-documented to produce imidazole derivatives, including substituted imidazoles, under mild thermal conditions (Hodge, 1953; Nursten, 2005). The key improvement here is explicit use of 2NH3 (addressing the previous criticism that one NH3 cannot provide two ring nitrogens) and an additional HCHO unit (addressing the C4\u2192C5 carbon balance). The stoichiometry is fully balanced: C4H8O4 + CH2O + 2NH3 \u2192 C5H6N2O + 4H2O + H2, where the H2 removal is driven by UV/TiO2 oxidative aromatization. Montmorillonite concentrates and templates the reactants (Sources 9431, 15641).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Maillard-type sugar-amine cyclization of ribose with ammonia to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation for aromatization, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ribose (C5) + 2NH3 \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (C5N2) + 4H2O + H2(UV-driven). Multi-step mechanism: (1) Ribose C-1 + NH3 \u2192 glycosylamine (ring-opened imine); (2) Amadori rearrangement gives amino-ketose; (3) Second NH3 attacks C-3 carbonyl; (4) Intramolecular cyclization between the two amino groups through C-2 forms the five-membered imidazole ring; (5) UV-driven oxidative aromatization with loss of H2O and H2; (6) C4-C5 fragment of ribose becomes the -CH2CHO side chain. Both nitrogen atoms come from separate NH3 molecules.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ribose-amine reactions (Maillard chemistry) are well-known to produce imidazole and pyrazine derivatives from pentose sugars and ammonia/amino acids under mild heating (Ledl & Schleicher, 1990; Yaylayan, 2003). The direct cyclization of ribose with two equivalents of ammonia to give imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is stoichiometrically balanced: C5H10O5 + 2NH3 \u2192 C5H6N2O + 4H2O + H2. This represents the most atom-economical route to the target intermediate. Montmorillonite templating and UV-driven aromatization provide the necessary catalysis and thermodynamic driving force (Sources 9431, 15641, 15918).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated HCN solutions (>0.01 M), mildly alkaline pH ~9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"4 HCN \u2192 (HCN)4 = DAMN. Sequential oligomerization: HCN dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 HCN trimer (aminomalononitrile) \u2192 HCN tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN). Montmorillonite clay concentrates HCN and provides surface catalysis for the stepwise oligomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN is one of the most well-established reactions in prebiotic chemistry (Sanchez et al., 1967; Ferris & Orgel, 1966). DAMN is a key intermediate for nucleobase synthesis and heterocycle formation. Mineral surfaces including montmorillonite enhance the oligomerization (Sources 9365, 21200, 21196, 9357, 6362).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 1: imine formation and cyanide addition\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 7-9, prebiotic pool with accumulated reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imidazole-4-acetaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 imine (Schiff base); imine + HCN \u2192 alpha-aminonitrile (histidyl aminonitrile). Step 1: condensation of the aldehyde with ammonia to form Im-CH2-CH=NH. Step 2: nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the imine carbon gives Im-CH2-CH(NH2)CN. This two-step sequence is the classic Strecker aminonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is explicitly identified in the literature as a key pathway for prebiotic histidine formation (Source 21332). The general Strecker mechanism involving aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN to form alpha-aminonitriles is one of the most well-established prebiotic reactions (Sources 21188, 985, 21192). Levine et al. (2008) demonstrated enantioselective amino acid synthesis under prebiotic Strecker conditions (Source 15388).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 672398.9078998566, "success": false, "error_message": "Unterminated string starting at: line 486 column 13 (char 27485)"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-18T04:35:53.225758", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\